<BYLINE>By MIKE EMBRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARROLLTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The driver of a pickup truck that
collided with a church bus in a fiery weekend crash was charged
with 27 counts of murder Monday after blood tests showed he was
legally drunk at the time.
   Larry Mahoney, 34, of Worthville was served with warrants at
Humana Hospital-University of Louisville, where he is in serious
condition, officials said. A guard has been posted at his door,
police said.
   Carroll County Commonwealth's Attorney John Ackman said he will
not hesitate to seek the death penalty in the Saturday night crash
on Interstate 71 that killed 27 people returning from a church
outing at an amusement park.
   Investigators from the National Transportation Safety Board said
at a news conference that the converted school bus did not meet
post-1977 safety requirements for a caged fuel tank.
   Joseph T. Nall, an NTSB board member, said the bus's fuel tank
had a 3-inch gash in it and had been pushed back 26 inches by the
impact of the crash.
   When asked if a caged tank might have prevented the fire that
enveloped the bus after the accident, Nall said, ``That's the
ultimate question we'd like to answer, but now it would be
premature.''
   Tests on Mahoney found a .24 blood alcohol level, said Capt.
Neal Brittain of the LaGrange state police post. Under state law, a
blood alcohol level of .10 creates the legal presumption of
intoxication.
   District Judge Stanley Billingsley denied bond. Mahoney will be
arraigned once he is released from the hospital, according to the
district court order.
   The case will go to the grand jury on June 6, Ackman said.
   Federal safety officials began an inquiry Monday into the
collision. Nall said investigators attempted to interview Mahoney
on Monday, but ``he would not talk to investigators for reasons of
his own.''
   Nall also said that the 1977 Superior bus with a Ford chassis,
which the manufacturer said was equipped to carry 66 passengers and
a driver _ the number aboard the night of the crash _ did not
appear to be overloaded.
   Some survivors have said the seats that were supposed to hold
three people were too small, resulting in some people hanging in
the aisle.
   ``It is not something we have corroborated to our
satisfaction,'' said NTSB spokesman Alan Pollock.
   Pollock said investigators on Monday examined the accident site,
about 45 miles northeast of Louisville, where Mahoney's northbound
Toyota pickup truck slammed head-on into the First Assembly of God
bus in the southbound lanes.
   In addition to checking the emergency exit, investigtors would
check the rescue process, maintenance records of the bus and their
drivers' records, said Alan Pollock, a spokesman with the National
Transportation Safety Board.
   ``We also want to talk to some of the survivors and witnesses to
the accident,'' Pollock said, and investigators hope to get ``some
kind of profile on the pickup truck and what it might have been
doing that night.''
   Authorities said it still isn't known why the truck was
traveling the wrong way.
   State officials said they hope to have positive identification
of all the bodies by Tuesday.
   The state medical examiner, Dr. George Nichols, said at a news
conference Monday that all of the victims died from smoke
inhalation. ``There was no significant bodily injury,'' he said.
   The Kentucky Post reported Monday that Mahoney pleaded guilty in
1984 to drunken driving and was fined $300 plus court costs and
$140 for traffic school. His license also was suspended for six
months, the newspaper said.
   His blood-alcohol level in the 1984 case was .16 percent, the
newspaper said.
   A friend of Mahoney's, Dennis Mefford, said he was with Mahoney
until about 2{ hours before the accident occurred. He said Mahoney
was very tired from having worked a double shift at M&amp;T Chemical
Co. in Carrollton.
   ``I can't remember seeing him drive in that bad a shape,''
Mefford said. ``It's really tore everybody up around here that
something his tragic could happen. It's unbelievable, simple
unbelievable.''
   Pollock also said the driving records of Mahoney and the bus
driver, John Pearman, would be reviewed.
   State police trooper Jim Mudd said state police investigators
talked briefly with Mahoney but did not disclose the conversation
because the case is still under investigation.
   Dental charts of the victims were sent to the University of
Louisville on Monday for matching with dental records, said David
Jones of the state medical examiner's office.
</TEXT>
