<DESCRIPT>  MONTEREY; COUNTY; ANIMAL; DEATH; SHOOTING; FARM; TRIAL  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Two Monterey County ranchers pleaded not guilty Thursday to charges of
illegally importing tigers, leopards and jaguars to their sprawling property
and charging hunters to kill them at close range.;    Then the ranchers, Floyd
Patterson and his wife, Dawn, walked outside King City Municipal Courthouse
and told reporters that charging people to kill the endangered animals is
exactly what they did.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  RANCHERS PLEAD NOT GUILTY
BUT OUTSIDE COURT, THEY SAY EXOTIC CATS WERE
KILLED  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Shorter version ran on page 2B of the Morning Final.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     "Well, sure we had a little business going there," Patterson said, one hand
on his enormous brass belt buckle engraved "California Ram Hunt" -- the name
of his ranch. "What's the difference if they put the thing to sleep in a zoo
or if somebody wants to mount it on the wall and appreciate it?";    Federal
and state investigators charge Patterson with purchasing a number of
endangered animals, including Bengal tigers, for "big game hunts" on his ranch
in southeastern Monterey County. Investigators say the third-generation
Monterey County rancher charged hunters to shoot the animals and take their
stuffed carcasses home as trophies. He is charged with 27 misdemeanors; Dawn
Patterson faces four counts.;    Kenneth J. Oravsky, a taxidermist who
allegedly prepared the trophies for Patterson, also was charged with 28
misdemeanor counts. The three face up to a year in prison and a $1,000 fine
for each misdemeanor.;    The majority of the charges involve violations of
endangered species laws and permit procedures.;    Monterey County Municipal
Court Judge Alan Hedegard set June 10 for the Pattersons' trial. No trial date
has yet been set for Oravsky.;    Federal officials also are looking into the
case.;    Investigators say some of the animals, which hunters paid up to
$3,500 to kill, were shot less than 100 feet from their cages. Others, too
tame to leave their enclosures, were shot in the cages and dragged outside for
photographs of the hunters with their catch, according to court records.;   
While most of the customers who came to the ranch have not been identified,
one client, Nicholas Miljevich of Saratoga, was charged in a separate
complaint with possessing a dead tiger, leopard and mountain lion. He asked
the court Thursday for a public defender to represent him.;    The Pattersons'
lawyer, Singh Aulakh of Visalia, said he would mount a political defense of
his clients, charging that their civil rights have been violated, though he
did not mention how. He also threatened to file suit against the county. While
acknowledging that the animals were killed at the Patterson ranch, he will
argue that shooting the sometimes toothless, elderly cats in their cages was
"more humane" than letting them die natural deaths.;    "I don't see any big
deal, I don't see any big deal to this at all," Aulakh said. "Yes, they were
shot on the grounds of Patterson ranch, but you should see what I have on my
wall. In a way they're putting an animal out of its misery. My God, if you
look at the pictures of these animals, I think you'll agree that this is the
best thing that could have happened to them.";    Like many ranchers in these
rolling foothills, Patterson has long conducted legal boar and ram hunts on
his property. But early in the spring of 1990, animal dealer Thurston Comstock
of Dragoon, Ariz., approached them about buying exotic cats for hunts, Dawn
Patterson told investigators. They had previously bought bighorn sheep and
goats from Comstock for hunting.;    She told investigators that Comstock
delivered two Bengal tigers and one black panther, a leopard and other animals
to their ranch.;    Some of the animals had been sedated, caged and placed in
the center of a truck trailer, investigators said, and the rear of the trailer
was then filled with sheep to obscure the cages from agricultural inspectors
at the state line.;    After arrival, the cats were kept in livestock trailers
for a few days and fed goat meat and chickens, Dawn Patterson said.;    In a
telephone interview last week, Comstock denied transporting exotic animals to
the Pattersons' ranch.  </TEXT>
