<BYLINE>By ROB WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associate Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARROLLTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Ford Motor Co. executive said
today a protective cage around the fuel tank of a church bus
probably would not have prevented a fire that killed 27 people.
   The testimony came at Larry Mahoney's trial on 27 counts of
murder in a wrong-way collision between the bus and Mahoney's
pickup. His attorneys say he unknowingly may have drunk
vodka-spiked soda pop before the May 14, 1988 crash.
   Twenty-four youngsters and three adults died in the accident on
Interstate 71 near here after flames consumed the bus from the
Radcliff First Assembly of God Church.
   Although a cage probably would not have prevented the fire,
former Ford vice president Thomas Feahney testified, ``there was
technology available that could have prevented this tragic
accident.'' He did not elaborate.
   The automotive engineer said the impact caused gasoline to
squirt ``like a flame thrower'' into the passenger section.
   On Monday, defense attorneys sought to establish that the former
school bus had safety defects that caused it to burst into flames.
The victims died of smoke inhalation or burns rather than of
injuries from the impact.
   ``Part of the defense has been the claim of involuntary
intoxication,'' defense attorney William Summers told reporters,
explaining the significance of testimony that a friend gave Mahoney
a cocktail of Diet Pepsi and vodka.
   ``To voluntarily drink something, you've got to have some idea
of what you're drinking,'' Summers said.
   Mahoney, 36, a factory worker from rural Owen County, is charged
with 27 counts of murder, 12 of assault, 42 of wanton endangerment
and one of drunken driving.
   His blood-alcohol level after the crash tested as high as 0.24
percent _ nearly 2{ times the state's definition of intoxication,
according to earlier testimony.
   Among those testifying Monday was Phil Downey, a longtime friend
of Mahoney's who was with him at a gathering he left less than an
hour before the 10:55 p.m. crash.
   Downey recalled Mahoney asking Kelly Osborne, a friend at the
gathering, what he was drinking. He said Osborne gave Mahoney a cup
of Diet Pepsi and vodka, saying, ``This is better for you than any
ld beer you ever drank.''
   Mahoney drank the mixture, Downey testified.
   Under cross-examination by Assistant Attorney General Paul
Richwalsky Jr., Downey said Mahoney appeared drunk when he drove
away.
   ``He shouldn't have been driving,'' Downey said.
   Summers said he would try to prove Mahoney didn't know what was
in the cup.
   The defense contends unsafe design of the 1977 school bus is to
blame for the deaths. A federal investigation after the crash found
the bus's exposed fuel tank prone to fire.
   Also testifying Monday was state Fire Marshal John William
Martin, who said the fire wouldn't have been prevented by a
protective cage around the bus' gas tank. The blaze erupted after a
piece of the bus's suspension punctured the tank.
   Martin said it couldn't be determined if the thick black smoke
that filled the bus and was blamed for most of the deaths was
caused by the burning of gasoline alone or the burning of plastic
seat covers and cushions.
</TEXT>
