<BYLINE>By GUY COATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man demanding to talk with Louisiana
State University's basketball coach entered the outer cage of LSU's
Bengal tiger mascot Wednesday but gave up after a five-hour
standoff, authorities said.
   LSU spokesman Gary Ballard said that the intruder had threatened
to free the 13-year-old, 500-pound tiger but that marksmen with
tranquilizer guns were nearby. The man had also claimed to have a
bomb in a bag, Ballard said.
   At one point, students who came to watch chanted: ``Tiger bait!
Tiger bait!'' _ the cry raised at LSU sporting events when the
opposing team enters.
   The man was recognized by students as Moacyr ``Bruno'' Cezar, an
ardent fan of the basketball team who lives in LSU's athletic
dormitory in return for doing work around the place.
   ``He wants a job. He has some sort of problem with his temporary
visa. He says he wants a work permit,'' said Ballard. At one point,
negotiators passed a document through the bars to him. Ballard said
it was ``an application for employment.''
   Cezar surrendered at 10:10 p.m. after talking with Jose Vargas,
the Spanish-speaking LSU center who is from the Dominican Republic.
Accompanied by a priest and two detectives, Cezar was taken to the
police station.
   No charges had been filed by late Wednesday night.
   ``He's upset, man. He's going to be all right. He'll talk to you
tomorrow,'' Vargas said.
   The coach, Dale Brown, was in Florida, but his wife, Vonnie, and
some of LSU's Spanish-speaking basketball players were among those
trying to talk Cezar out. Cezar is a Brazilian who speaks mainly
Portugese.
   Brown was told of the incident but had no immediate plans to
return, Ballard said.
   Cezar had entered a cage surrounding the one in which the tiger
is kept by taking the keys from the animal's trainer, who was
cleaning the cage, said Ballard.
   ``This individual walked up and demanded the keys to the cage.
He threatened the trainer. The trainer thinks he had a gun, but
he's not sure,'' Ballard said. No weapons or bomb were found when
the standoff ended, he said.
   Ballard said the intruder for a time held both the trainer and
an unidentified young woman inside the cage as his hostages.
   A police SWAT team stood about 100 yards away during the
standoff.
   By nightfall, hundreds of students, LSU officials and reporters
had flocked to the cage between the football stadium and the arena
where the basketball team plays.
   LSU spokesmen said the intruder had been befriended by Brown and
had become one of the LSU basketball team's most enthusiastic fans.
Ballard said the man also had been enrolled in an LSU program to
improve his English.
   ``He's been a volunteer observer of LSU basketball for the past
two years and has been quite close to Coach Brown,'' said Ballard.
