<DESCRIPT>  ANIMAL; SMUGGLING; HUNT; DEATH; MONTEREY; COUNTY; CRIME; PROBE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  A Monterey County ranch where smuggled Bengal tigers, jaguars, leopards and
mountain lions were released from cages and killed for sport is one of more
than a dozen such illegal hunting operations that federal officials say they
are investigating nationwide.;    In some cases, animals were tranquilized,
tied to trees and then shot, federal officials said. In others the animals
were released in an area the size of a football field where customers who had
paid large sums of money shot them, officials said.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  'RIGGED' TIGER KILLS PROBED ACROSS U.S.  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Last two paragraphs ran only in PM editions.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     "You're talking about Tony the Tiger here," said Bill Talkin, a special
agent for the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service investigating the Monterey County
case. "It's really atrocious.";    At the 5,000-acre Patterson Ranch in
southern Monterey County, the farthest one of the rare cats got from its cage
before it was shot was 100 feet, witnesses said. One of the animals was so
docile it wouldn't leave its cage while the trophy hunters who paid to kill it
stood waiting, Talkin said. The cat was shot to death in its cage and skinned,
Talkin said.;    But one of the ranchers charged in the case, Floyd Lester
Patterson III, 44, said in a telephone interview that the 38 criminal charges
filed against him, his wife and a taxidermist are overblown.;    "The way
they're talking about it, they're talking like it was a crapshoot or
something. It wasn't nothing like that," Patterson said. "I'm a hunter; I lead
guided hunts. There's nothing wrong with that.";    Patterson's attorney did
not return several calls made to his Visalia office.;    Talkin said federal
authorities confiscated photographs and videotapes of black jaguars, tigers,
leopards and mountain lions being shot on the Patterson property. He said they
were tipped off by a former assistant to Kenneth Oravsky who helped the
taxidermist skin, stuff and mount the endangered cats for clients of the
ranch.;    Talkin said that hunters came from all over the United States to
hunt at the ranch, but he said the number of people who participated in the
shoots is unclear.;    David McMullen, assistant regional manager of the U.S.
Fish and Wildlife Service in Portland, Ore., said that trade in endangered
species in the United States is relatively rare. With only several thousand
Bengal tigers left in the world, he termed dealing in them and other big cats
for profit and shooting them "despicable.";    "It's a rigged shoot, I don't
like to call it a hunt," McMullen said. "I guess their desire is to get a
trophy for their trophy room. And there are people willing to pay money to
shoot an animal when it comes out of a cage.";    Leopard, jaguar and mountain
lion hides cost about $5,000 on the black market, McMullen said. A Bengal
tiger hide can run more than $10,000, he said.;    Many of the animals used in
the black market hunting trade are zoo animals sold when they are too old or
sick to exhibit, then funneled to smugglers who deal in the endangered species
for profit, investigators said.;    The Patterson Ranch is a working cattle
ranch that has been in the same family for several generations, Monterey
County officials said. But most of the cattle on the ranch have been sold as
feed became scarce during the drought. As a result, the Pattersons appear to
have stepped up their operation of what they call "California Ram Hunt" -- so
named for the legal guided hunting tours of exotic sheep, boars and deer they
run on the ranch.;    ...; Investigators say it is unclear how long the
illegal hunts were taking place.;    Patterson, his wife Dawn Patterson and
Oravsky could each be sentenced to five years in jail and be ordered to pay
$50,000 for each animal shot on the ranch. They will be arraigned in King City
Municipal Court on May 9.  </TEXT>
