<DESCRIPT>  LETTER  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  I'm writing to urge people to boycott Circus Vargas.;    The life of a circus
animal is one of misery and deprivation. Every major humane society in the
United States is against circuses due to their abuse of animals, and many
European countries have banned or restricted the use of animals in
entertainment.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Editorial  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  FOR ANIMALS, CIRCUS MEANS ONLY MISERY AND
DEPRIVATION  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Letters to the Editor  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Living quarters for the animals are often as small as possible for ease of
handling on the road, and the animals are confined to those cages when not
performing. This means, for example, that tigers -- which in the wild may
range over 1,000 square miles -- are restricted to cages as small as 12 feet
by 6 feet. Unable to move around normally, the animals become bored and
neurotic. Often, the cages are too hot or too cold, and it is common for
animals to go without food, water or veterinary care for long periods of time
due to the circus' tight time schedule.;    Consider the "tricks" circus
animals perform. Fire inspires fear in all animals; the only way an animal
would jump through a hoop of fire is if the only alternative is punishment.
Circus animals perform tricks because they have been brutalized with whips,
prods and sharp hooks.;    In addition, circus rings commonly mix animals of
incompatible species. Lions and tigers are mortal enemies, as are bears and
the big cats. Animal deaths and injuries have occurred from such abnormal
combinations.;    When one knows the truth behind the happy circus facade,
it's difficult to be entertained by it.;    Those of us living on the Central
Coast are lucky to have ample opportunity to see wild animals. We have
endangered whales in Monterey Bay year-round, elephant seals at Ano Nuevo,
deer at Big Basin and sea otters, sea lions and sea birds in Santa Cruz and
Monterey.;    If you are a parent thinking of taking your children to the
circus, please consider these humane and natural alternatives. If we are to
live in a peaceful world, we must give the animals peace as well.;    --
Michelle Waters; Santa Cruz  </TEXT>
