sprawling ranch.;    Four men and seven women were selected Tuesday. More than
250 prospective jurors were called up for the case.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  JURORS PICKED IN CATS TRIAL
HUNTING-RANCH OWNERS INDICTED ON 44 COUNTS  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Floyd and Dawn Patterson were arrested in April for allegedly charging
hunters a fee to kill tigers, lions and jaguars, including some old and
toothless animals that refused to budge from their cages and were shot from
less than 100 feet away.;    In a 44-count indictment, investigators accused
the Pattersons of charging hunters $3,500 to kill the wild cats, get pictures
taken with the dead animals and then take them home after they were stuffed.
The indictment cited the killing of two Bengal tigers, one spotted leopard, a
black jaguar, a crossbred cat and two mountain lions.;    The misdemeanor
counts, most of which deal with violations of the endangered-species law and
permit process, carry a maximum penalty of one year in jail and a $1,000 fine
each.;    Jury selection began Monday. About 8,000 people live in King City,
and many prospective jurors were dismissed after saying they knew the
Pattersons well enough to be possibly biased.;    Some potential jurors were
excused after saying they couldn't stand the thought of helpless animals being
killed.;    "I just feel too strongly about shooting caged animals," one woman
said before she was dismissed.;    Outside the courtroom, the Pattersons'
attorney, Singh Aulakh, said his clients did not do anything wrong by giving
hunters a chance to kill some unusual wild game at their California Ram Hunt
ranch. He said there's no state law against wild-game hunts.;    "It's not a
crime to shoot these animals," Aulakh said. "I don't know what all the fuss
and excitement is about.";    In early June, Monterey County taxidermist
Kenneth Oravsky, 45, pleaded guilty to six misdemeanor counts of illegal
possession of endangered animals. In exchange, lawyers promised him a maximum
sentence of six months in jail and a $10,000 fine. He also agreed to testify
against the Pattersons.  </TEXT>
