<LEADPARA>  In the first such case in California, two Monterey County ranchers were
convicted Tuesday of 42 counts of violating state endangered species laws when
they illegally imported exotic animals to their sprawling property and charged
hunters to kill the big game at close range.;    A King City Municipal Court
jury deliberated for seven hours before finding Floyd Patterson, 35, and Dawn
Patterson, 31, guilty of every count on which they were tried. Investigators
say Floyd Patterson charged hunters up to $3,500 to shoot the animals and take
their stuffed carcasses home as trophies. He was convicted on 35 counts and
Dawn Patterson on seven counts as an accomplice.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  TWO RANCHERS CONVICTED IN BIG-GAME CASE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Mercury News Wire Services contributed to this report.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     "I don't think it's ever going to happen in the state of California again,"
said the prosecutor in the case, Monterey County Deputy District Attorney Russ
Scott. "I don't think anybody's going to take the chance.";    During the
trial, Scott detailed an extensive commercial hunting operation through a
calendar and business ledgers seized at the ranch. Hunters paid a package fee
to the Patterson business, California Ram Hunt, and were given food and
lodging at the ranch house.;    Cat hides in courtroom;  Jurors were shown
photographs of Floyd Patterson and his hunter clients posing with freshly shot
Bengal tigers, a spotted leopard, a black jaguar and several other species of
cats listed by the federal government as endangered species. Cat hides
confiscated from the Patterson's Lockwood ranch lay on the floor of the
courtroom during much of the proceedings, and a Bengal tiger skull was passed
around to jurors.;    Prosecution witnesses testified at the two-week trial
that eight cats were killed at the Patterson ranch between May and July 1990.
The witnesses included an accomplice in the hunting operation, the taxidermist
who skinned and mounted the dead animals. He pleaded guilty to reduced charges
earlier this month in exchange for his testimony.;    "I'm stunned," Dawn
Patterson said.;    "I don't hold anything against the jury," said Floyd
Patterson who has promised to appeal. "I don't think they understood all the
evidence.";    Taxidermist depicts shootings;  The taxidermist, Kenneth
Oravsky, 45, told jurors that each of the animals was taken in its cage to an
isolated part of the ranch and then shot by a hunter with gun ready standing
about 150 feet away. All of the animals, he testified, were shot less than 100
feet from their cages. One, too tame to leave the enclosure, was dragged out
by a lasso around its neck and shot just outside the door of the cage.;   
Oravsky testified that during the first cat hunt at the ranch, the
hunter-client fainted and had to be revived with CPR before he could fire his
gun and kill the animal.;    Despite the graphic material evidence that the
cats were killed at the mountainous ranch property, prosecutors had a
complicated time constructing a case against the Pattersons. California law
does not specifically prohibit the killing of cats which are not native to the
state. Of the cats shot at the ranch, only the mountain lion is found in
California in the wild. Prosecutors told the jury the Pattersons imported the
other cats through Thurston Comstock, an animal dealer in Arizona.;   
Animals' care regulated;  The care and treatment of exotic animals brought
into the state is strictly regulated, however, through an elaborate permit
process that controls their transportation, confinement and sale. It is on
violations of those laws, as well as injury to California mountain lions, that
the Pattersons were tried.;    "I think we're seeing that people recognize
that we do have a population of endangered species that exists around the
world," said John Foster, a California Fish and Game investigator who worked
with the prosecutor in the case. "I think people recognize that these
populations need safeguards and so we have regulations that try to prevent the
commercial sale of parts of these animals.";    "By no stretch of the
imagination were any of these animals hunted," Foster said. "They were brought
here through a black market, pulled out of their cages and shot.";    Similar
cases in other states;  Scott said the conviction marks the first time in
California such a big-game business has been uncovered and tried. Other cases
have been prosecuted recently in Texas and Oklahoma, he said.;    The attorney
for the Pattersons, I. Singh Aulakh, declined last week to mount a defense,
calling prosecution of the case "inept.";    Monterey County Municipal Court
Judge Alan Hedegard scheduled the Pattersons sentencing for Aug. 2. They face
a maximum penalty of a year in jail and a $1,000 fine on each count.  </TEXT>
