<TEXT>     The complaint says people paid up to $3,000 to kill an endangered animal,
which was released from a cage and shot almost immediately.;    District
Attorney Klar Wennerholm of Monterey County said Oravsky, a taxidermist, then
skinned and stuffed the big cats and mounted them for the customers to take
home as trophies. He said customers often bought videotapes of the kill.;   
Federal officials are still looking for a man who they suspect was paid to
smuggle the animals from Arizona, Missouri, Colorado and Mexico. It is a
violation of federal law to deal in tigers, mountain lions and leopards for
profit, and it is against both state and federal law to shoot any of those
animals under most circumstances.;    The complaint says some of the animals
were zoo animals sold when they were too old to be kept on exhibit.;   
Wennerholm said that, from May to July 1990, the three months when he
investigated activity at the ranch, at least nine animals were killed. He said
it is unclear when the shootings began and how long they continued.;    While
most of the customers who came to the ranch have not yet been named,
Wennerholm did release the name of one client: Nicholas Mitchell Miljevich of
Los Gatos. He was charged in a separate complaint with possessing a dead
tiger, leopard and mountain lion.;    Investigators serving a search warrant
on the Patterson ranch in November said they confiscated tiger skulls and
skins as well as photographs and videotapes of the game hunt.;    "I've never
seen anything like that before," said Bob Koch, a California Fish and Game
supervisor who visited the ranch. "I was really surprised that, in this quiet
community, that this kind of thing could happen.";    Hunting is fairly common
on the mountainous cattle ranches of Monterey County -- everything from
squirrels to wild turkeys, pigs and sheep. Some ranchers are licensed as
hunting guides and legally charge people to hunt on their land.;    But,
Wennerholm said, "In the more than 20 years I've been in this job, I've never
seen anything like this. It looks like they just let them out of the cages and
then shot them.";    The three suspects, who could not be reached for comment
Tuesday, are scheduled to be arraigned May 9 in King City Municipal Court. If
convicted, they could face six months in jail and a $5,000 fine.  </TEXT>
