<HEAD>Elephants Wow Manhattan With Midnight March</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The oom-pah-pah of a tuba and the jangle of a
tambourine were the first clues that things were not quite normal
in the Queens Midtown Tunnel early today.
   Then a police van came out on the Manhattan side with flashing
lights. It braked in front of the more than 100 spectators gathered
along the road and its megaphone crackled to life: ``Do yourself a
favor and don't touch the cages.''
   What brought out the crowd, which ranged from grandmothers to
infants?
   ``Word of trunk,'' one spectator said.
   It was Ringling Bros. and Barnum &amp; Bailey Circus' annual
three-mile parade of animals as the big top moved into Madison
Square Garden for its six-week run.
   The caged lions and tigers came first, 14 of them in two strands
of cages linked together and pulled by trucks. The animals paced
back and forth.
   ``Here pussycat,'' someone in the crowd yelled.
   ``Living things in Manhattan that are not people, and are not
cockroaches!'' yelled Amy Slaton, a 30-year-old art critic. ``This
is the happiest night of my life.''
   The crowd roared as the elephants appeared at the tunnel exit.
Ninteen were linked with long strands of chains, walking mainly two
abreast. The cry went up, ``Wooo-oooo! Elephants! Elephants! AAAAll
Right!''
   Paula Van Meter was wearing an elephant nose and ears in honor
of her sixth trip to the parade.
   ``Sometimes dignitaries get to ride on the elephants,'' the
41-year-old Brooklyn resident said. ``That would be worth running
for office.''
   ``I wish we had a little baby elephant,'' said a child.
   After the elephants came 15 horses, five zebras and six camels.
   The rear was brought up by a Department of Sanitation street
sweeper, busy at work.
   One elephant rider was Richard Dunne, a 37-year-old lawyer from
Baltimore, who said he bought the ride at a charity auction. He
would not say how much he paid, only that it was expensive and
worth the money.
   ``It was like a gigantic horse,'' Dunne said. ``It's so fresh
for New York. Everyone is smiling and happy, even the cops were
happy.''
</TEXT>
