<HEAD>Outdoors: Skunk Trapper</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY708</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL SCHULZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   When her husband suggested the family could use more cash,
Janice Henke got herself a job _ trapping skunks.
   ``When I come in from an unsuccessful skunk expedition, my
husband won't let me come in the house unless I take off every
stitch, including my sneakers, and hang them in the tree,'' says
Mrs. Henke, who lives far enough outside of Glens Falls, N.Y., that
there are no neighbors nearby.
   Then it's into a shower and ``I leave my clothes outside for a
week or so.''
   Most of the skunks live through the ordeal and only about one in
20 takes a shot at her with its personal perfume, she says.
   As both a licensed wildlife rehabilitator and licensed nuisance
wildlife agent, she must first decide which situation applies when
a potential customer calls.
   ``You have to decide who's distressed. Is it the people or the
creature?'' she says. ``Generally, it's the people.''
   The animal is in distress if it can't get away.
   If the animal could leave if it wanted to, but doesn't care to
just now, it's the people who are in distress.
   If it's the people who are distressed, the cost is $25 per skunk.
   Normally, it's a simple matter of setting a box trap outside the
hole the skunk is using to get under a building or through a fence.
But there are exceptions.
   ``The lady called me in a panic because, she said, `there's a
skunk in my washing machine,''' Mrs. Henke says. ``I'd never had
that before.''
   The skunk apparently fell into the machine after climbing
through a basement window broken by the woman's children.
   Skunks are a major problem in upstate New York where they are
attracted to man's warm dwellings and groomed lawns,'' said Mrs.
Henke in an interview during this year's North American Wildlife
and Natural Resources Conference in Denver. She is a lobbyist for
the National Trappers Association and executive vice president of
Furbearers Unlimited.
   As winter approaches, skunks begin to den up and sometimes a
dozen or more will hole up under a house or mobile home.
   Disputes among skunks are settled in a manner that leaves a very
unpleasant aroma for the homeowner above.
   Mrs. Henke uses a wire box trap, ``which is pretty good sized,
so when the animal considers entering it, it won't touch his sides
or back. I used a Twix bar for bait, caramel flavor.''
   Next morning, if the homeowner finds an occupied trap ``I'll
come with my skunk blanket.''
   It's an ``old yellow blanket'' with a hole in it so she can
watch the animal while she moves up on it, holding the blanket up
so it can't see a human.
   Some skunks react aggressively to the approaching blanket,
stamping their front paws.
   She waits, then lowers the blanket over the cage, ``figuring if
he's going to spray he's going to do it now or never.''
   Then she wraps the cage in the blanket, places the package in
the back of the pickup truck and takes it to a spot on state land
where ``hopefully there aren't any houses around.''
   ``Then I uncover the end of the cage, remove the door, and if he
doesn't come out by himself, I pick the cage up and give him a
heave-ho, and he rolls over and gets up and trundles off through
the woods.''
   While buildings, with such things as warm water pipes, are a
source of comfort, lawns are a source of food. Lawns are full of
grubs, primarily the larvae of June bugs and Japanese beetles, she
says.
   ``They hunt those by smell and they dig and it looks like a lawn
has been ravaged by a pick of hogs if the skunk has been really
industrious,'' she says.
   Then, it's time for the wire trap and old yellow blanket.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

