<HEAD>Moscow Circus Accused of Mistreating Its Performing Bears</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Toronto Humane Society claims the famed
Moscow Circus is mistreating its performing bears by confining them
in small cages and on Monday it threatened court action.
   David Bain, a Humane Society investigator, said the 12 brown
bears are being psychologically mistreated by being held in cages
measuring about 3 feet by 4{ feet.
   He said the society will file a complaint accusing the circus of
cruelty to animals if it doesn't provide larger cages or better
treatment by Wednesday.
   Arthur Fogel, a promoter of the Soviet company's tour that
includes shows in New York City next month, said the bears are
``treated great'' and the Humane Society was misleading the public.
   Fogel, of Concert Productions International, said the bears are
excercised daily and Bain's contention that they are confined up to
16 hours a day ``is totally inaccurate.''
   He said the bears are raised by their Soviet trainers from birth
and are in excellent health. ``I'm glad the trainers can't
understand English,'' he added. ``If they heard what is being said
about their bears they'd be very upset.''
   Bain said the bears' daily training routines, in which they walk
on their front legs and ride bicycles, are not adequate exercise
for the animals, which weigh from about 195 to 300 pounds.
   He said the bears ``are suffering from severe behaviorial
problems'' because of the psychological strain of confinement.
   The circus begins a three-week run Wednesday at the Canadian
National Exhibition in Toronto, with the bears performing once or
twice a day.
   Bain also criticized the circus for its treatment of a pregnant
Siberian tiger shipped to Canada. He said the animal gave birth
during a 15-day sea voyage from the Soviet Union to Montreal.
   Circus manager Ted Thrasher said the tiger was transported by
sea because it would have been traumatized had it been moved by
airplane.
   Bain insisted the tiger should not have been moved at all.
   He said the other animals in the circus appeared to be healthy.
</TEXT>
