adoption counselors.;   "If you're in here every single day doing this, you
get really worn down," she said. "I couldn't do this every day. It would
desensitize you -- either that or you'd go insane.";   The dog has a high
temperature, something Sandquist had suspected. Back in his cage she had
noticed him barking hoarsely, as if he had a sore throat.;   These are signs
that the dog probably has kennel cough -- a generic name for a variety of
airborne respiratory diseases commonly transmitted in kennels. Although the
cough is easy and inexpensive to cure, Sandquist said the shelter doesn't have
the space or money to care for every dog who contracts it.;   "This is what's
hard," she said, slipping her patient a couple of biscuits, which he gobbles
down in seconds. "I know that with just a little bit of medicine this dog
would be fine. But a healthy dog could take his place. Instead of putting a
sick dog up for adoption, even though it's treatable, we can put a healthy dog
in his cage.";   Sandquist once again reaches for the leather leash and leads
dog number 220160 back to his concrete cage where, for the next hour or so, he
can stare through his wire fence at the terrier snoozing across the aisle, or
bark hoarsely with the other dogs he hears all around him.;   Then it's off to
"E.R.," the euthanasia room.;   "It smells like death," Sandquist said of the
euthanasia room. "That's the first thing, the biggest thing, that you notice.;
  "Once they get out there, they definitely know (what's going to happen). You
can just see it by the way they react.";   Sometimes, she said, her decisions
on who lives and who dies has nothing to do with health or temperament. Often
there's just not enough room to house all of the 38,000 animals that arrive at
the shelter throughout the year.;   Some of these Sandquist can't get out of
her mind. Like the droopy-eared cocker spaniel puppies that came in several
months ago. They were perfectly healthy, "gorgeous" dogs, she said, but she
had to walk them back to E.R.;   "We weren't allowed to put puppies into
adoption then. That was the only reason," she said. "That made me cry.
Perfectly beautiful animals.";   Sandquist figures she's hardened a bit since
then. Although when her day is done she still takes home sadness, the stress
of her job often manifests itself in anger instead of tears. Sometimes she
finds herself irritated by little things, or snapping at someone for no good
reason, she said.;   On her first day of work she was a wreck, Sandquist
remembers.;   "I hated it. I told everybody, 'I can't ever do that again. I
don't want to make that decision, I don't want to be the one.' ";   With time,
though, she decided she couldn't lay the responsibility on anyone else.;   Her
stress also emerges as anger toward people who think Humane Society employees
don't care about animals, or that they get some sort of pleasure out of
euthanizing them.;   But Sandquist, 27, doesn't fit the description of such a
monster. She's an active, single woman, whose short blond hair and blue eyes
convey her Swedish citizenship. After graduating from Penn State a year ago
with a double major in Spanish and international relations, she moved to San
Jose, where she lives with her two cats and her boyfriend.;   Despite the sad
parts of her job, she sees a good side.;   The good side is finding just the
right owner for just the right cat, or bending the rules occasionally and
getting the county vet to treat an animal, even though its time is supposed to
be up.;   "I make up for having to send that one dog down by doing something
positive in another area," she said.;   Earlier that morning, Sandquist was
checking an orange tabby named Hubcap who'd been surrendered by its owner the
day before. The cat's profile, provided by the previous owners, said they were
giving him up because he scratched a child. That's one point against adoption,
Sandquist said.;   But now he's being very cooperative, letting Sandquist
check his teeth without too much protest, and responding with purrs to
Sandquist's gentle voice and touch.;   Often, she'll stay with an animal in
the E.R. and hold it while it's injected, to help them through it, she said.; 
 "This is my kind of cat," she said of the orange tabby who has now jumped
from the exam table and onto the counter. "Big, male, really friendly. If
there was something wrong with it I'd probably go to my supervisor" and ask
for special treatment.;   Sandquist makes a note on the cat's paperwork,
saying it doesn't do well with children, and then puts him into a fresh cage
in the adoptable cat room. This one will have two more weeks worth of chances.
These are moments that make the job easier, she said.;   "In a way this job is
a nice change of pace," she said. "In here, I really have close contacts with
the animals. It's tough to have to play God, but since the majority of them
get put up for adoption, that outweighs the bad."  </TEXT>
