<HEAD>City Pet Store Features Exotic Animals For Display</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COLLEEN DISKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leopards and llamas and doves. Oh my.
   Those are among the exotic denizens of Animal Kingdom, a pet
store that serves as a zoo for urban children and home for show
business animals.
   In addition to the usual assortment of puppies, kittens,
reptiles and fish, the store has a leopard that stars in
commercials, a duck that used to appear on a children's program and
an organ grinder's monkey that shares his cage with a toy fox
terrier.
   ``We have one rule about our exotic animals _ they have to be
able to work,'' said general manager Steve Maciontek. ``That way
they aren't just sitting in their cages all the time. That's not
good for them.''
   So Joshua the llama pulls a cart at parades, Luther the leopard
appears in commercials, and the 30-odd doves in the store are
rented out for weddings, serving as centerpieces at the bride and
groom's table.
   Maciontek said the 10,000 square-foot store has a special
exhibitor's license that allows it to house and display the 35
exotic animals it rents out, but never sells.
   When they're not earning their keep, the store's animals serve
as entertainment for customers and school children who visit the
store for free tours.
   ``When I get an inner city kid that's never been to a zoo, and I
see his eyes light when he sees the leopard, it makes it all
worthwhile,'' Maciontek said.
   The store on the city's north side averages at least two tours a
day during summer. Maciontek said the purpose is not only to expose
children to animals, but to teach them about caring for pets and
exotic animals.
   Twice a month, employees take animals to hospitals and nursing
homes, offering ``pet therapy'' to patients, Maciontek said.
   ``What we're trying to get across with our store is that animals
are only as wild as we make them,'' he said. ``People are shocked
when we go right into the cages to clean the animals, and the
leopard or the tiger licks our hands.''
   Only one of the store's animals is endangered, a rhinoceros
hornbill named Harriet. The 10-pound black-and-orange horned bird
is similar to a toucan.
   Federal officials inspect the store every year, checking to see
that the animal cages are large enough and that they're being fed
the right diet.
   Maciontek said the store occasionally gets complaints from
animal rights activists who don't think traditionally wild animals
should be in captivity. But he contends that the animals are
well-cared for and fare better than they might if they were in the
jungle.
</TEXT>
